00:01:58.670 --> 00:02:00.610
of its natural and
cultural endowments

00:02:00.610 --> 00:02:03.230
vis-a-vis contemporary
challenges it faces.

00:02:03.230 --> 00:02:07.080
I hope the book will bring this
important but much neglected

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:09.730
region into sharp
international focus.

00:02:09.730 --> 00:02:11.480
Life in the Himalaya
explores the mountain

00:02:11.480 --> 00:02:13.850
in its four distinct stages.

00:02:13.850 --> 00:02:17.760
One, the natural
phase, which comprises

00:02:17.760 --> 00:02:20.360
Himalaya's geobiological
consolidation and development

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:26.800
of human culture that symbolizes
moksha, or the salvation,

00:02:26.800 --> 00:02:29.400
salvation through human
expression of mountain temple

00:02:29.400 --> 00:02:30.970
metaphor.

00:02:30.970 --> 00:02:33.790
It points to an
imminent human impulse

00:02:33.790 --> 00:02:35.990
to reconstruct the
mountain and therefore

00:02:35.990 --> 00:02:38.802
a yearning for ascension.

00:02:38.802 --> 00:02:41.010
The second phase, the cultural
phase, of the Himalaya

00:02:41.010 --> 00:02:44.540
covers nomadic pastoral
communities for the last 15,000

00:02:44.540 --> 00:02:49.620
years, and it reaches the climax
with commercial deforestation

00:02:49.620 --> 00:02:53.810
during British raj, who
sowed the seeds of discontent

00:02:53.810 --> 00:02:57.450
and conflict between the
people, the local communities,

00:02:57.450 --> 00:02:59.550
and the state.

00:02:59.550 --> 00:03:02.430
And then the third phase,
the mechanical phase,

00:03:02.430 --> 00:03:06.020
which is marked by burgeoning
human population growth,

00:03:06.020 --> 00:03:09.110
urbanization, and large-scale
infrastructure and dam

00:03:09.110 --> 00:03:11.910
projects, which are causing
unprecedented ecosystem

00:03:11.910 --> 00:03:14.500
degradation and
biological extinctions.

00:03:14.500 --> 00:03:17.590
And finally, the need for a
network phase, or networking

00:03:17.590 --> 00:03:20.340
phase, which necessitates
information sharing

00:03:20.340 --> 00:03:23.480
and institutional
cooperation in search

00:03:23.480 --> 00:03:26.280
of the safe space
for the Himalaya.

00:03:26.280 --> 00:03:28.800
Now this is the
kind of a context.

00:03:28.800 --> 00:03:31.330
And before I get to
my slides, I also

00:03:31.330 --> 00:03:43.010
want to read a para from
chapter two of my proposed book.

00:03:43.010 --> 00:03:45.500
This is titled "The
Lure Of the Mountain,

00:03:45.500 --> 00:03:48.390
Sacrifice and the
Moksha." "The Himalaya

00:03:48.390 --> 00:03:50.150
predates the arrival
of humans on Earth,

00:03:50.150 --> 00:03:53.190
but celebration of its grandeur
is entrenched in the lore

00:03:53.190 --> 00:03:55.250
and legend of the mountain.

00:03:55.250 --> 00:03:57.420
The Himalayan memoir
forms an integral part

00:03:57.420 --> 00:03:59.560
of the shared
inheritance of Asia,

00:03:59.560 --> 00:04:02.570
where humans witnessed the
final phase of Himalaya

00:04:02.570 --> 00:04:06.160
rise towards the end of
the Pleistocene glaciation.

00:04:06.160 --> 00:04:09.280
The grand spectacle that
unfolded before our ancestors'

00:04:09.280 --> 00:04:13.270
eyes must have been an edifying
experience for the mind.

00:04:13.270 --> 00:04:18.529
Hindus often speak of such
experience in terms of Ananda,

00:04:18.529 --> 00:04:22.510
which presages boundless sense
of fulfillment and peace.

00:04:22.510 --> 00:04:25.490
And it means much more
than joy and bliss.

00:04:25.490 --> 00:04:27.620
"The massive rock that
stands high above the ground

00:04:27.620 --> 00:04:29.840
is not merely a
conglomeration of stone,

00:04:29.840 --> 00:04:32.560
but to the worst
humanity, irrespective

00:04:32.560 --> 00:04:35.170
of color, creed,
faith, and nationality,

00:04:35.170 --> 00:04:38.200
it is a living magnet that pulls
the weak and the strong alike

00:04:38.200 --> 00:04:39.720
towards it.

00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:42.700
The Himalaya's unequal vocal
exhortation by the visitor

00:04:42.700 --> 00:04:46.130
goes beyond a simple description
of the scenic beauty,

00:04:46.130 --> 00:04:49.080
the sparkling snowfields,
the flower tapestry

00:04:49.080 --> 00:04:51.880
and the fragrance, the diversity
of life and its colors.

00:04:54.692 --> 00:04:56.400
The journey alone
elevates the experience

00:04:56.400 --> 00:04:59.780
to a deeper understanding
and meaning of life."

00:04:59.780 --> 00:05:03.130
The Himalayan legend
abounds in symbols

00:05:03.130 --> 00:05:05.730
that underpin man's abiding
faith in the sacredness

00:05:05.730 --> 00:05:07.880
and divinity of the mountain.

00:05:07.880 --> 00:05:11.970
Willi Unsoeld--" I'm not able
to pronounce it properly.

00:05:11.970 --> 00:05:13.540
It's Unsoeld.

00:05:13.540 --> 00:05:16.340
He was a Swiss-American,
the first American

00:05:16.340 --> 00:05:19.500
to scale Mount
Everest in 1963, was

00:05:19.500 --> 00:05:22.330
so enthralled by the divine
pull of Nanda Devi, which

00:05:22.330 --> 00:05:24.650
is about 8,000 meters,
that he named his daughter

00:05:24.650 --> 00:05:27.720
Nanda Devi after the mountain.

00:05:27.720 --> 00:05:31.830
Nanda Devi Unsoeld was
a proficient mountaineer

00:05:31.830 --> 00:05:34.140
and accompanied her father
on several such mountain

00:05:34.140 --> 00:05:35.650
expeditions.

00:05:35.650 --> 00:05:37.240
Sadly, during one
of the expeditions

00:05:37.240 --> 00:05:42.610
to trek in Himalaya, young Nanda
Devi died on September 8, 1976,

00:05:42.610 --> 00:05:44.620
at age 22.

00:05:44.620 --> 00:05:49.740
She had gone against
team physicians' advice

00:05:49.740 --> 00:05:55.350
to go down to a lower level
because of the snowstorm.

00:05:55.350 --> 00:05:57.240
Nanda Devi was a
wildlife biology major

00:05:57.240 --> 00:05:59.240
and had developed great
interest in conservation

00:05:59.240 --> 00:06:02.020
of endangered species,
such as cats of the East.

00:06:02.020 --> 00:06:04.520
Even though she was averse
to mountain climbing

00:06:04.520 --> 00:06:07.630
as a full-time vocation,
she felt almost mystical

00:06:07.630 --> 00:06:10.150
about the climb she
was about to undertake.

00:06:10.150 --> 00:06:13.420
Before setting off for what
turned out to be her last time,

00:06:13.420 --> 00:06:16.640
she told an interviewer,
which I quote here.

00:06:16.640 --> 00:06:19.300
"I can't describe it, but
there is something within me

00:06:19.300 --> 00:06:22.740
about this mountain
ever since I was born."

00:06:22.740 --> 00:06:23.730
Unquote.

00:06:23.730 --> 00:06:27.470
Willi Unsoeld buried his
daughter around Camp 4

00:06:27.470 --> 00:06:32.280
at 7,300 meters under the
snows of her namesake mountain.

00:06:32.280 --> 00:06:34.920
There is no way to verify
if Willi Unsoeld had known

00:06:34.920 --> 00:06:37.510
that in Garhwal Himalaya
Nanda is metaphorically

00:06:37.510 --> 00:06:39.920
used for daughters.

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:42.640
My wife, when addressed as
Nanda by her grandmother,

00:06:42.640 --> 00:06:45.400
caught me by surprise
some years ago.

00:06:45.400 --> 00:06:51.400
